<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="255" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,680,1594,1621]" box="[136,680,1594,1621]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
<heading box="[136,680,1594,1621]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,680,1594,1621]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName authority="Rohdendorf, 1962" authorityName="Rohdendorf" authorityYear="1962" box="[264,680,1594,1621]" family="Archizelmiridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Archizelmirinae">
Archizelmirinae 
<bibRefCitation author="Rohdendorf, B. B." box="[465,680,1594,1621]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" pagination="444 - 502" refId="ref4344" refString="Rohdendorf, B. B. (1962). Order Diptera. In: Rohdendorf, B. B. (Ed.), Fundamentals of paleontology, volume 9, Arthropoda, Tracheata, Chelicerata. Smithsonian Institution Libraries and National Science Foundation, Washington, D. C., pp. 444 - 502 [In Russian, English translation 1991]" type="book chapter" year="1962">Rohdendorf, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,778,1667,2093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,296,1667,1693]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Composition.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation location="Jurassic" municipality="Early Cretaceous of Asia" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus box="[301,357,1668,1694]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Type</typeStatus>
genus from the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:821F87D93F36FF9C85E3F9FEAF8BFAC8:0F6960143F36FF9C877CF947A869F941" box="[535,624,1667,1693]" municipality="Early Cretaceous of Asia" name="Jurassic" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Jurassic</location>
and the 
<collectingMunicipality pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Early Cretaceous of Asia</collectingMunicipality>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="255" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,778,1667,2093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,312,1740,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Flagellomeres not differentiated; cervical region not long.Wing with Sc incomplete, extremely short, extending to level of 
<emphasis box="[370,426,1813,1838]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">m-cu</emphasis>
; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[458,466,1831,1845]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">1</subScript>
, long, extending far beyond M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[161,186,1867,1881]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">1+2</subScript>
furcation; Rs base sloping backwards; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[658,684,1867,1881]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">4+5</subScript>
apically branched; basal part of M present as non-sclerotized fold; CuP thin, complete; anal lobe of moderate size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="255" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,778,1667,2093]" lastBlockId="1.[810,1452,158,1301]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,305,1958,1984]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Grimaldi, D. &amp; Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V." box="[321,592,1957,1984]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" pagination="368 - 381" refId="ref3746" refString="Grimaldi, D., Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V. (2003) The Mesozoic family Archizelmiridae (Diptera: Insecta). Journal of Paleontology, 77 (2), 368 - 381. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 0022 - 3360 (2003) 077 &lt;0368:" type="journal article" year="2003">
Grimaldi 
<emphasis box="[437,495,1957,1983]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">et al</emphasis>
. (2003)
</bibRefCitation>
considered the backwards slope of Rs and the very weak development of Sc as the apomorphic characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Rohdendorf" authorityYear="1962" box="[564,709,2030,2056]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Archizelmira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[564,709,2030,2056]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Archizelmira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both characters occur in the new species described below, although the slope of Rs is rather slight. The 
<typeStatus box="[1329,1377,159,185]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">type</typeStatus>
genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Rohdendorf" authorityYear="1962" box="[810,955,194,220]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Archizelmira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,955,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Archizelmira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated into a subfamily of its own with two putative apomorphies, 
<emphasis box="[1112,1143,231,256]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">viz</emphasis>
. the extremely short Sc and the recurrent Rs base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[810,1452,158,1301]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
Some characters have been missed in previous descriptions of the genus. The incomplete CuP (A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1407,1415,357,371]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">1</subScript>
of authors) has been mentioned as a familial character of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Grimaldi et al., 2003)" baseAuthorityName="Grimaldi" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[810,1268,410,437]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Archizelmiridae (
<bibRefCitation author="Grimaldi, D. &amp; Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V." box="[1009,1260,410,437]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" pagination="368 - 381" refId="ref3746" refString="Grimaldi, D., Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V. (2003) The Mesozoic family Archizelmiridae (Diptera: Insecta). Journal of Paleontology, 77 (2), 368 - 381. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 0022 - 3360 (2003) 077 &lt;0368:" type="journal article" year="2003">
Grimaldi 
<emphasis box="[1123,1175,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">et al</emphasis>
., 2003
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Indeed, CuP is often indistinct on compressions due to its thinness, but the present study found a complete CuP in the new species (
<figureCitation box="[818,884,518,544]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,235,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[180,1408,189,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-25@3.[180,1408,189,1928]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Archizelmira jarzembowskii sp. nov., holotype PIN 1255/2218, Kubekovo, J2. A, B, Positive impression, photo (SEM, uncoated) and drawing of total view. C, D, Photograph of negative impression, basal part of wing (SEM, uncoated) and total view. Scale bars = 0.2 mm. Arrows mark bM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820870/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), as well as in specimens of the 
<typeStatus box="[1253,1301,519,545]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">type</typeStatus>
species from both localities (
<figureCitation box="[991,1116,554,580]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[136,235,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[185,1402,189,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[185,1402,189,1928]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Archizelmira kazachstanica. A, B, PIN 2997/3284, Karatau, J3. Wing, positive impression, B, Base of wing, negative impression. C, D, PIN 2997/3141, negative impression, Karatau, J3, pubescence and basal part of wing, Shar Teg, J3 (SEM, uncoated). E, PIN 4270/2244, total view of wing, Shar Teg, J3 (SEM, uncoated). Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Fig. 2B, E</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1187,1295,554,581]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Archizelmira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="baissa">
<emphasis box="[1187,1295,554,581]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">A. baissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1314,1438,554,580]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[136,235,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1602]" captionTargetId="figure-111@5.[151,1436,194,1602]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Archizelmira baissa, holotype PIN 3064/9039, Baissa, K1. A–D, Wing, pubescence of veins (SEM, uncoated). E, F, Wing, total view and basal part. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820880/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Fig. 3E, F</figureCitation>
). The basal part of M, present in the new species as a nonsclerotized fold, is recorded for the first time in the family thanks to the excellent preservation of the wing from Kubekovo (
<figureCitation box="[942,1007,698,724]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,235,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[180,1408,189,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-25@3.[180,1408,189,1928]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Archizelmira jarzembowskii sp. nov., holotype PIN 1255/2218, Kubekovo, J2. A, B, Positive impression, photo (SEM, uncoated) and drawing of total view. C, D, Photograph of negative impression, basal part of wing (SEM, uncoated) and total view. Scale bars = 0.2 mm. Arrows mark bM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820870/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). However, such fold is also distinct on the well-preserved wings of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rohdendorf" authorityYear="1962" box="[1136,1328,734,761]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Archizelmira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kazachstanica">
<emphasis box="[1136,1328,734,761]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">A. kazachstanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Shar Teg (
<figureCitation box="[868,991,770,796]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[136,235,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[185,1402,189,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[185,1402,189,1928]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Archizelmira kazachstanica. A, B, PIN 2997/3284, Karatau, J3. Wing, positive impression, B, Base of wing, negative impression. C, D, PIN 2997/3141, negative impression, Karatau, J3, pubescence and basal part of wing, Shar Teg, J3 (SEM, uncoated). E, PIN 4270/2244, total view of wing, Shar Teg, J3 (SEM, uncoated). Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Fig. 2D, E</figureCitation>
). It is visible as well on the photographs accompanying the original description, where it has not been discussed (
<bibRefCitation author="Grimaldi, D. &amp; Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V." box="[999,1251,842,869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" pagination="368 - 381" refId="ref3746" refString="Grimaldi, D., Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V. (2003) The Mesozoic family Archizelmiridae (Diptera: Insecta). Journal of Paleontology, 77 (2), 368 - 381. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 0022 - 3360 (2003) 077 &lt;0368:" type="journal article" year="2003">
Grimaldi 
<emphasis box="[1113,1166,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">et al</emphasis>
., 2003
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 1.2–4). The anal lobe of the wing of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Rohdendorf" authorityYear="1962" box="[1131,1276,878,904]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Archizelmira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1131,1276,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Archizelmira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reduced or moderately developed (
<figureCitation box="[1071,1139,914,940]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,235,1575,1599]" captionTargetBox="[157,751,206,1547]" captionTargetId="figure-389@6.[141,772,206,1551]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Shape of wings of Archizelmira. A, A. jarzembowskii sp. nov., holotype PIN 1255/2218, Kubekovo, J2. B–D, A. kazachstanica, PIN 2997/3284, 2239/2030, 2239/2031, Karatau, J3. E, A. baissa, holotype PIN 3064/9039, Baissa, K1. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820882" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820882/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), whereas it is very strongly developed in the three other genera (‘anal lobe of wing 90 degrees or more’ in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hippa, H. &amp; Vilkamaa, P." box="[1033,1319,986,1013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" pagination="121 - 144" refId="ref3814" refString="Hippa, H. &amp; Vilkamaa, P. (2005) The genus Sciarotricha gen. n. (Sciaridae) and the phylogeny of recent and fossil Sciaroidea (Diptera). Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, 36, 121 - 144. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631205788838492" type="journal article" year="2005">Hippa &amp; Vilkamaa, 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[810,1452,158,1301]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
Thus the incomplete CuP is not a character of 
<taxonomicName box="[810,992,1058,1084]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Archizelmiridae</taxonomicName>
but another putative synapomorphy of the Cretaceous clade (
<taxonomicName box="[1079,1207,1094,1120]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Zelmiarcha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1079,1207,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Zelmiarcha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ (
<taxonomicName box="[1261,1421,1094,1120]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Burmazelmira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1261,1421,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Burmazelmira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName box="[810,955,1130,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" genus="Archimelzira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,955,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">Archimelzira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)). It supplements the diagnostic characters of the 
<taxonomicName authority="LUKASHEVICH, 2022" authorityName="LUKASHEVICH" authorityYear="2022" box="[881,1075,1166,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Archizelmiridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" status="subfam. nov." subFamily="Burmazelmirinae">Burmazelmirinae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1082,1233,1166,1192]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1082,1233,1166,1192]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" rank="subFamily">subfam. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(see below), which also include the reduction of the basal part of M, the strongly pronounced anal lobe, and the characters pointed out by 
<bibRefCitation author="Grimaldi, D. &amp; Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V." box="[887,1136,1274,1301]" pageId="1" pageNumber="255" pagination="368 - 381" refId="ref3746" refString="Grimaldi, D., Amorim, D. S. &amp; Blagoderov, V. (2003) The Mesozoic family Archizelmiridae (Diptera: Insecta). Journal of Paleontology, 77 (2), 368 - 381. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 0022 - 3360 (2003) 077 &lt;0368:" type="journal article" year="2003">
Grimaldi 
<emphasis box="[996,1045,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="255">et al</emphasis>
. (2003)
</bibRefCitation>
, which were listed above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
